datasets.description_clean: SENSE-42: A multimodal Human-Computer Interaction dataset from Simulated Environment for Neurocognitive User State Evaluation Overview SENSE-42 is a publicly available, multimodal dataset designed to support the study of user state monitoring during extended computer interaction sessions via neurocognitive, physiological and behavioural responses. Combining high-resolution neurophysiological recordings with behavioral and subjective data, this dataset enables research on the alternations of attention, mental/physical fatigue, cognitive workload, and related subjective indices at a very early stage. The dataset was collected from 42 participants over a 2-hour continuous interaction session, during which participants engaged in a series of designed tasks on a desktop computer with a mouse and keyboard. The experimental tasks were conducted within a fully simulated desktop operating system environment, designed to closely mimic real-world computer usage scenarios. This setup mirrors how people typically use computers in daily life. The simulated experiment program also enables the comprehensive capture of the mouse and keyboard data, synchronized with a high refresh rate monitor at 144 Hz. Recordings were collected in a noise-insulated room, minimizing external interruptions from the environment or the experimenter. The project includes both the raw dataset (available via Synapse) and the analysis codebase (available on GitHub, WIP) for replicability and reuse. Modalities and Data Contents The dataset includes multimodal signals across the following channels: Behavioural Data Participant interaction logs collected via PsychoPy, including task performance metrics, reaction times, and mouse & keyboard status per frame. Electroencephalography (EEG) 32-channel scalp EEG recordings collected with the BioSemi ActiveTwo system at 1024 Hz. EEG signals are stored in .bdf format. datasets.description_clean: The adult mammalian brain is composed of distinct regions that have specialized roles. To dissect molecularly this complex structure, we conducted a project, named the BrainStars (B) project, in which we sampled ~50 small brain regions, including sensory centers and centers for motion, time, memory, fear, and feeding. To avoid confusion from temporal differences in gene expression, we sampled each region every 4 hours for 24 hours, and pooled the sample sets for DNA-microarray assays. Therefore, we focused only on spatial differences in gene expression. We then used informatics to identify candidates for (1) genes with high or low expression in specific regions, (2) switch-like genes with bimodal or multimodal expression patterns, and (3) genes with a uni-modal expression pattern that exhibit stable or variable levels of expression across brain regions. We used our findings to develop an integrated database (http://brainstars.org/) for exploring genome-wide expression in the adult mouse brain.

datasets.name: BrainLat_dataset
datasets.description_clean: Dataset description The Latin American Brain Health Institute (BrainLat) dataset comprises multimodal neuroimaging data of 780 participants from Latin American. The dataset includes 530 patients with neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's disease (AD), behavioral variant frontotemporal dementia (bvFTD), multiple sclerosis (MS), Parkinson's disease (PD), and 250 healthy controls (HCs). This dataset (62.7 ± 9.5 years, age range 21–89 years) was collected through a multicentric effort across five Latin American countries to address the need for affordable, scalable, and available biomarkers in regions with larger inequities. The BrainLat dataset is the first regional collection of clinical and cognitive assessments, anatomical magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), resting-state functional MRI (fMRI), diffusion-weighted MRI (DWI), and high density resting-state electroencephalography (EEG) in dementia patients. In addition, it includes demographic information about harmonized recruitment and assessment protocols. The dataset is publicly available to encourage further research and development of tools and health applications for neurodegeneration based on multimodal neuroimaging, promoting the assessment of regional variability and inclusion of underrepresented participants in research. Individuals The BrainLat dataset contains neuroimaging and cognitive data from 780 subjects, including patients with AD (N =278), bvFTD (N =163), PD (N =57) and MS (N =32), and HCs (N =250). Recruitment centers Participants were enrolled in clinical sites from the Multi-Partner Consortium to Expand Dementia Research in Latin America (ReDLat), a regional effort to harmonize participant enrollment and neurocognitive assessment in multicentric studies. Five ReDLat countries were included (Argentina, Chile, Colombia, Mexico, and Peru). Dataset information A detailed description of the dataset can be found in Prado P, Medel V, Gonzalez-Gomez R, Sainz-Ballesteros A, Vidal V, Santamaría-Garc

datasets.description_clean: Dataset Description The Eye-BCI multimodal dataset provides an extensive collection capturing simultaneous electroencephalography (EEG), electrooculogram (EOG), electromyogram (EMG), high-speed video recordings, and synchronized eye-tracking. Participants' mental states and selected physical characteristics are also included, creating a solid foundation for examining ocular artifacts and eye-movement features in Brain-Computer Interface (BCI) applications. Four experimental paradigms are recorded to elicit various sensory-motor responses and their influence on ocular activity: Motor Imagery (MI), Motor Execution (ME), Steady-State Visually Evoked Potentials (SSVEP), and P300 speller tasks. Within the P300 paradigm, trials are organized into two folders to differentiate word-length conditions, one for four-letter target words and the other for five-letter targets. Dataset information A detailed description of the dataset is available in the following paper: Guttmann-Flury, E., Sheng, X. & Zhu, X. Dataset combining EEG, eye-tracking, and high-speed video for ocular activity analysis across BCI paradigms. Sci Data 12, 587 (2025). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41597-025-04861-9 Participants A total of 31 volunteers, including both left- and right-handed individuals, participated in this experiment across 63 sessions, amounting to approximately 46 hours of recording. The dataset includes 2520 trials for each of the Motor Imagery (MI), Motor Execution (ME), and Steady-State Visually Evoked Potentials (SSVEP) paradigms, and 5670 trials for the P300 paradigm. During the initial session, participants completed a questionnaire assessing their demographic information, physiological details, and psychophysiological states. datasets.name: HBI_scRNAseq
datasets.description_clean: The human brain immunity scRNAseq (HBIscRNAseq) study Our incomplete knowledge about etiology and plausible mechanisms of brain disorders is a major bottleneck for successful disease treatments. We analyzed single-cell transcriptomes of 113,457 human brain parenchymal immune cells across diverse neurological disorders, facilitating successful identifications of functionally diversified rare microglial populations associated with neurodegeneration. Moreover, additional incorporations of prior knowledge and independent unbiased information, as well as multimodal single-cell blood samples, into advanced systems-biology frameworks allowed us to elicit strategic coordination of innate and adaptive immunity in the human brain, which systemically reshapes immunophenotypes in varying pathophysiology. Our comprehensive characterization of all identified parenchymal immune cell populations illustrates wide functional spectrums of human brain immunity. Finally, we unified complementary observations from the qualitative and quantitative analyses into a plausible disease model, linked to aging-induced pathogenesis.

datasets.name: ANMerge
datasets.description_clean: ANMerge: A comprehensive and accessible Alzheimer’s disease patient-level dataset Background: Accessible datasets are of fundamental importance to the advancement of 30 Alzheimer’s disease (AD) research. The AddNeuroMed consortium conducted a longitudinal observational cohort study with the aim to discover AD biomarkers. During this study, a broad selection of data modalities was measured including clinical assessments, magnetic resonance imaging, genotyping, transcriptomic profiling and blood plasma proteomics. Some of the collected data were shared with third-party researchers. However, this data was incomplete, erroneous and lacking in interoperability. Methods: We systematically addressed several limitations of the originally shared data and provide additional unreleased data to enhance the patient-level dataset. Results: In this work, we publish and describe ANMerge, a new version of the AddNeuroMed dataset. ANMerge includes multimodal data from 1702 study participants. Conclusions: ANMerge is an information rich patient-level data resource that can serve as a discovery and validation cohort for data-driven AD research, such as for example machine learning and artificial intelligence approaches. See ANMerge: A comprehensive and accessible Alzheimer's disease patient-level dataset for details about the study

Methods Cells collected from cell sorting were encapsulated into oil droplets using a Chromium NextGEM Chip G (10X Genomics). Following reverse transcription and cDNA amplification, 5’ gene expression, immune repertoire, and feature barcode libraries were constructed following manufacturer protocols (v1.1). datasets.description_clean: Parkinson's DREAM Challenge Authors: Vaibhav Tripathi, Tav Pritesh Sethi, Richa Singh, Mayank Vatsa Affiliations: Indraprastha Institute of Information Technology, Delhi Summary Sentence We utilized a collection of simple and complex models ranging from mean, median to convolutional neural nets to test out the various features. We also designed an Object Oriented architecture in Python to help rapidly test featuresets. Background/Introduction What is the motivation for your approach? For the Parkinson's Disease Digital Biomarker DREAM Challenge (syn8717496), we started with simple basic features like mean, median, mode etc. for the accelerometer and gyrometer time series signals to find out if there are any distinction between normal and diseased subjects. Once, we have tested that we utilized CNN based features on the frequency domain of these signals to capture out any information between dimensions in a single sensor. We initially started with the approach developed by the recent paper by IBM called Deepsense architecture[1] but then moved on to a modification of the architecture. Methodology: We focussed on the separation on walk patterns - the normal walk pattern and the parkinsonian walk pattern. Each walk pattern would have a digital signature in terms of their time domain and frequency domain data. datasets.description_clean: 4Care Introduction We propose a personalized portable patient-driven data acquisition portal to help patients and providers gain inferences from reports and expand research and development through information extraction from text and image data. This will help caregivers keep track of their children's reports, and it will also help speed clinical trial breakthroughs through the availability of full records. The portal will foster data sharing across hospital institutions and foundations. Pitch Video Approach There are common platforms out there including Mychart and Care Everywhere network that propose a one-stop solution to manage patient records. However, outside patient clinics and local clinics are not involved and not every hospital is signed up with EPIC, as there are other EHR systems involved that make it difficult to aggregate patient records. Talking to caregivers and patients that we interviewed, we found that they all carry notebook binders around with them to a specialist visit with their children’s medical reports and imaging data. Background/Introduction Unlike traditional machine learning algorithms, deep learning can be used not only to predict an outcome such as drug sensitivity, but also to directly learn internal, lower-dimensional representations of the input data. The modular nature of deep learning models also makes it easier to integrate multiple data types. Instead of concatenating different feature types into a single dataset before training, distinct feature-encoding subnetworks for each type of data can be constructed, and then the learned representations can be concatenated and fed into a final prediction subnetwork. The study investigates emotional responses to VR video stimuli in both healthy controls and individuals with depression symptoms. datasets.description_clean: Fine-tuning ensemble methods for tabular EHR data Ivan Brugere, Nikhil Naik, Andre Esteva, Lav Varshney Salesforce Research This submission is publicly available Submission code is available at: https://github.com/ivanbrugere/ehrdc/ (public after final leaderboard phase) We find that traditional gradient boosting methods perform surprisingly well on large, tabular EHR datasets. Background/Introduction In this report, we focus on designing simple models with minimal feature engineering, model complexity, and hand-coding. Initially, our focus was on sequential models which aimed to separate patient sequences into contiguous healthy and unhealthy segments. But we found that static models outperformed these models and allowed greater model exploration within the budget constraints of the competition. A second principle we focused on was a common problem formulation which share pre-processing and featurization. This allowed for model selection over many models, and quick model development. Our final submission (syn21533058) achieves 0.9555 AUC without any domain-specific feature-engineering. Methods Our method is simple, minimizing the featurization and preprocessing needed for the prediction task. Our motivation was to show that very simple models would be effective on datasets on an order of magnitude larger than prior EHR work. In this context, tree-based classifiers likely find very robust groups of discriminating features. Preprocessing We use the "OMOP useful columns" metadata as the subset of features we'll process. We construct a single [\patient x \features] matrix. All concepts are mapped to a boolean presence/absence, not the real value, e.g. in the observation table. We treat age by unique years. datasets.description_clean: Title Downsampled single-nucleus RNA-seq data from 84 postmortem A9 and MTG brain regions were used to build neuropathology prediction models Summary As required for the SEA-AD Challenge, we built neuropathology prediction models using the provided training dataset comprising single-nucleus RNA-seq profiles from 84 postmortem human brain donors, including both Alzheimer’s disease (AD) and non-AD cases. The dataset included rich metadata containing donor demographics, cell-type classifications, and quantitative measures of AD pathology severity, including Braak stage, Thal phase, AD neuropathologic change (ADNC), CERAD neuritic plaque score, and immunohistochemical (IHC) markers such as percent AT8-positive, percent 6E10-positive, percent NeuN-positive, and percent GFAP-positive areas. Nuclei were isolated from two cortical regions implicated in AD pathology—the A9 region and the middle temporal gyrus (MTG). To minimize technical and biological bias, donor-level data were downsampled to achieve balanced cell-type representation while preserving overall tissue composition. Downsampled datasets were processed and integrated using R and Python, with Seurat employed for normalization, quality control, cell-type aggregation, and computation of donor-level transcriptomic summaries. From these standardized datasets, we derived biologically interpretable features capturing cell-type proportions, highly variable gene expression, mitochondrial and cell-cycle activity, and dysregulated AD-related gene modules. Cell–cell communication patterns were inferred using CellChat, providing complementary information on intercellular signaling. After variance filtering and correlation-based pruning, the resulting donor-level feature matrices were used to train supervised machine learning models predicting multiple neuropathologic and immunohistochemical outcomes, including ADNC, Thal phase, Braak stage, CERAD score, and IHC burdens (AT8, 6E10, NeuN, GFAP). Our models were demonstrated to have good generalization

datasets.description_clean: Deep Learning Approaches for Predicting TB Status Using Audio from Elicited Coughs, Demographic Information, and Clinical Data Team: Blue Team Code: syn50545508 Filip Mulier and Dan Rafter, MD Flywheel.io, Minneapolis, Minnesota USA Will you be able to make your submission public as part of the challenge archive? Yes Summary Sentence The proposed approach uses STFT for audio preprocessing , a modified convolutional neural network that accepts both image and tabular data, and ensemble averaging. Background/Introduction The challenge put forth by Sage Bionetworks Cough Diagnostic Algorithm for Tuberculosis required the prediction of pulmonary tuberculosis (TB) based on the acoustic qualities of tussive episodes recorded over the duration of 2 weeks. With both clinical diagnosis and disease transmission heavily reliant on cough duration, productivity, and frequency it is a natural biomarker for experimental methodology for advanced detection ^1^ ^2^ Convolutional neural networks applied to the magnitude of the short term Fourier transform (STFT), also known as spectrogram, have shown promising results for classifying a wide range of sounds. Typically the mel transformation is used on the frequency bands to more closely match the frequency resolution of the human auditory system. However, for the classification of cough pathology, experiments ^3^ have demonstrated improved results using the frequency bands without a mel transformation. The cough recordings naturally exhibit a wide variation over a relatively small data set of 1082 subjects. The scoring metric for this challenge is area under the ROC curve (AUROC). In order to improve our estimate of the AUROC metric, 5 fold cross-validation was used for model validation versus a simple training/validation split . A resnet34 network was used for sub-challenge 1(audio only input) while resnet34 network modified to accept tabular input was used for sub-challenge 2 (audio and tabular data). Inference in both cases was done

Schulz ^1,2^ 1: Cluster of Excellence on Multimodal Computing and Interaction, Saarland University, 66123 Saarbruecken, Germany; 2: Computational Biology \& Applied Algorithmics, Max Planck Institute for Informatics, 66123 Saarbruecken, Germany; 3: Graduate School of Computer Science, Saarland University, 66123 Saarbruecken, Germany Introduction In our approach, we use DNase1-seq data, Position Frequency Matrices (PFMs), and Transcription Factor (TF) ChIP-seq data. RNA-seq data as well as chromatin shape predictions are not considered. Briefly, we compute TF binding affinities for 557 TFs and compute DNase1-seq coverage in each bin. As it was shown before that TFs bind to regions of open chromatin (Pique-Regi et al., 2011) we expect DNA accessibility to be an informative feature that can be used together with the sequence based TF binding predictions to model tissue specific TF binding. In addition,we try to account for tissue variability using ensemble learning. And congratulations to our top-performing teams! --- The International Brain Tumor Segmentation (BraTS) challenge. BraTS, since 2012, has focused on the generation of a benchmarking environment and dataset for the delineation of adult brain gliomas. The focus of this year’s challenge remains the generation of a common benchmarking environment, but its dataset is substantially expanded to ~4,500 cases towards addressing additional i) populations (e.g., sub-Saharan Africa patients), ii) tumors (e.g., meningioma), iii) clinical concerns (e.g., missing data), and iv) technical considerations (e.g., augmentations). Specifically, the focus of BraTS 2023 is to identify the current state-of-the-art algorithms for addressing (Task 1) the same adult glioma population as in the RSNA-ANSR-MICCAI BraTS challenge, as well as (Task 2) the underserved sub-Saharan African brain glioma patient population, (Task 3) intracranial meningioma, (Task 4) brain metastasis, (Task 5) pediatric brain tumor patients, (Tasks 7 & 8) global & local missing data, (Task 9) useful augmentation techniques, and importantly (Task 6) the algorithmic generalizability across Tasks 1-5. Details for each ‘Task’ are listed in the rest of this documents under Challenges. Notably, all data are routine clinically-acquired, multi-site multiparametric magnetic resonance imaging (mpMRI) scans of brain tumor patients. The BraTS 2023 challenge participants are able to obtain the training and validation data of the challenge at any point from the Synapse platform. These data will be used to develop, containerize, and evaluate their algorithms in unseen validation data until August 2023, when the organizers will stop accepting new submissions and evaluate the submitted algorithms in the hidden testing data. Ground truth reference annotations for all datasets are created

Glioblastoma patients have very poor prognosis, and the current standard of care treatment comprises surgery, followed by radiotherapy and chemotherapy. The International Brain Tumor Segmentation (BraTS) Challenges —which have been running since 2012— assess state-of-the-art machine learning (ML) methods used for brain tumor image analysis in mpMRI scans. The RSNA-ASNR-MICCAI BraTS 2021 challenge utilizes multi-institutional multi-parametric magnetic resonance imaging (mpMRI) scans, and focuses on (Task 1) the evaluation of state-of-the-art methods for the segmentation of intrinsically heterogeneous brain glioblastoma sub-regions in mpMRI scans. Furthermore, this year's challenge also focuses on (Task 2) the evaluation of classification methods to predict the MGMT promoter methylation status at pre-operative baseline scans. Participants are free to choose whether they want to focus only on one or both tasks. NOTE: Task 2 is being hosted by Kaggle. datasets.name: Wearables for gait in Parkinson's Disease and age-matched controls (WearGait-PD)
datasets.description_clean: Background Algorithms are playing an increasingly vital role in medical devices. Understanding the impact of curating accessible datasets on algorithm development and evaluation, the FDA collaborated with the U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) and Johns Hopkins School of Medicine to establish this open-access dataset containing raw (unprocessed) inertial measurement unit (IMU) and sensorized insole data from 100 individuals with Parkinson’s Disease (PD) and 85 age-matched controls synchronized to a gait reference system. Frame-by-frame annotation of participant actions during gait and balance tasks was incorporated into the dataset using video cameras synchronized to all systems. To expand the utility of this dataset, all data are associated with demographic information and clinical evaluations (e.g., medications, DBS-status, MDS-UPDRS scores). This wearables dataset can serve as a tool to assess novel algorithms for deriving gait metrics through wearables, establish distributions and variability of wearable-derived gait metrics, and provide correlational information about clinical evaluations and wearable-derived gait metrics, among other things. This wiki brings together in a hyperlinked format everything needed to work with these data, including: description of the data collection procedures, data processing and alignment, annotation processes, and data quality control processes. Explore the links below for additional details regarding the data and processing approaches, how to access the data, publications using these data, and contact information. datasets.description_clean: MISAW - Part of the Endoscopic Vision Challenge Welcome to the The “MIcro-Surgical Anastomose Workflow recognition on training sessions” (MISAW) sub-challenge as a part of the MICCAI 2020 UPDATE: The full dataset is available for download here (synapse account required) The join paper has been accepted on Computer Methods and Programs in Biomedicine: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0169260721005265 --- Introduction Automatic and online recognition of surgical workflows is mandatory to bring computer-assisted surgery (CAS) applications inside the operating room. According to the type of surgery, different modalities could be used for workflow recognition. In the case where the addition of multiple sensors is not possible, the information available for manual surgery is generally restricted to video-only. In the case of robotic-assisted surgery, kinematic information is also available. It is expected that multimodal data would make easier automatic recognition methods. The “MIcro-Surgical Anastomose Workflow recognition” (MISAW) sub-challenge provides a unique dataset for online automatic recognition of surgical workflow by using both kinematic and stereoscopic video information on a micro-anastomosis training task. Participants are challenged to recognize online surgical workflow at different granularity levels (phases, steps, and activities) by taking advantage of both modalities available. Participants can submit results for the recognition of one or several granularity levels. datasets.description_clean: Single-cell multimodal glioma analyses reveal epigenetic regulators of cellular plasticity and environmental stress response Supplemental Data website OVERVIEW This page is intended to provide processed data for processed single-cell DNA methylation, single-cell transcriptomics, bulk mutation calls, bulk copy number alterations, bulk DNA methylation microarray beta-values, and bulk gene expression profiles presented in our Nature Genetics paper. Request to access raw data is available through the European Genome-Phenome Archive (EGAS00001005300). Questions? Please raise general questions related to processed tables or files in the Discussion tab. Abstract Glioma intratumoral heterogeneity enables adaptation to challenging microenvironments and contributes to therapeutic resistance. We integrated 914 single-cell DNA methylomes, 55,284 single-cell transcriptomes, and bulk multi-omic profiles across 11 adult IDH-mutant or IDH-wild-type gliomas to delineate sources of intratumoral heterogeneity. Local DNA methylation disorder was associated with cell-to-cell DNA methylation differences, elevated in more aggressive tumors, links with transcriptional disruption, and associated with environmental stress response. We demonstrated that in vitro, cells under hypoxia and irradiation stress increase local DNA methylation disorder and shift cell states. We identified a positive association between genetic and epigenetic instability that was supported in cohorts of bulk longitudinally collected DNA methylation data. Increased DNA methylation disorder associated with accelerated disease progression, and recurrently selected DNA methylation changes were enriched for environmental stress response pathways. Our work identifies an epigenetically facilitated adaptive stress response process and highlights the importance of epigenetic heterogeneity in shaping therapeutic outcomes. Challenge closed Thank you to all who participated! --- The International Brain Tumor Segmentation (BraTS) challenge has been focusing, since its inception in 2012, on generating a benchmarking environment and a dataset for delineating adult brain gliomas. The focus of the BraTS 2023 challenge remained the same: generating a standard benchmark environment. At the same time, the dataset expanded into explicitly addressing 1) the same adult glioma population, as well as 2) the underserved sub-Saharan African brain glioma patient population, 3) brain/intracranial meningioma, 4) brain metastasis, and 5) pediatric brain tumor patients. Although segmentation is the most widely investigated medical image processing task, the various challenges have been organized to focus only on specific clinical tasks. Each segmentation method was evaluated exclusively on the patient population it was trained on in each sub-challenge. In this challenge, we aim to organize the BraTS Generalizability Across Tumors (BraTS-GoAT) Challenge. The hypothesis is that a method capable of performing well on multiple segmentation tasks will generalize well on unseen tasks. Specifically, we will focus on assessing the algorithmic generalizability beyond each patient population and focus across all of them. The challenge is part of the official ISBI 2024 challenges! Join them now! {column} {column width=1} {column} {row} --> --- Alzheimer’s disease (AD) is the most common neurodegenerative disorder, affecting approximately 1 in 9 individuals (10.9%) aged 65 and older (1). It leads to progressive cognitive decline and dementia, severely impacting daily functioning and placing emotional, social, and financial strain on patients and their families (1). AD is characterized by deposition of hallmark pathological peptides across partially overlapping neuroanatomical and temporal axes (4-9). This process is generally believed to follow a stereotyped progression with amyloid beta (Aβ) plaques starting in the cerebral cortex and hyperphosphorylated Tau (pTau) aggregation (neurofibrillary tangles (NFTs)) starting in the brainstem and limbic system (4-9). Recent advances in single-cell transcriptomics have provided unprecedented insights into the cellular composition of the aging and diseased brain, generating rich, high-dimensional datasets that may reveal molecular signatures of vulnerability and resilience (11-14). When paired with quantitative measures of regional(2,15) or even per-cell pathological burden(21,22), these signatures can be associated with these classical disease hallmarks. A large number of these datasets lack these measures though, limiting associations to broader histopathological disease staging or even cases versus controls(14,16-20). To drive innovation at this frontier, we are launching a crowdsourced challenge calling on the research community to develop models that predict AD neuropathological burden from single-cell transcriptomic profiles. Neuropathological and single nucleus transcriptomics data for this challenge are derived from the Seattle Alzheimer’s Disease Brain Cell Atlas (SEA-AD) consortium. The SEA-AD consortium includes the Allen Institute for Brain Science, the University of Washi

Join them now! {column} {column width=1} {column} {row} --- Overview Understanding transcriptional regulation at individual cell resolution is fundamental to understanding complex biological systems such as tissues and organs. Emerging high-throughput sequencing technologies now allow for transcript quantification and chromatin accessibility at the single cell level. These technologies present unique challenges due to inherent data sparsity. Proper signal correction is key to accurate gene expression quantification via scRNA-seq, which propagates into downstream analyses such as differential gene expression analysis and cell-type identification. Congratulations to our top-performing teams! --- The International Brain Tumor Segmentation (BraTS) challenge. BraTS, since 2012, has focused on the generation of a benchmarking environment and dataset for the delineation of adult brain gliomas. The focus of this year’s challenge remains the generation of a common benchmarking environment, but similar to 2023 this dataset is substantially expanded to ~4,500 cases towards addressing additional i) populations (e.g., sub-Saharan Africa patients), ii) tumors (e.g., meningioma), iii) clinical concerns (e.g., missing data), and iv) technical considerations (e.g., augmentations). Specifically, the focus of BraTS 2024 is to identify the current state-of-the-art algorithms for addressing (Task 1) post-treatment glioma with a new dataset (Task 2) the underserved sub-Saharan African brain glioma patient population, (Task 3) radiotherapy meningioma with a new dataset, (Task 4) brain metastasis, (Task 5) pediatric brain tumor patients, (Tasks 7 & 8) global & local missing data, (Task 9) useful augmentation techniques, and (Task 10) pathology with a new dataset. Details for each ‘Task’ are listed in the rest of this documents under Challenges. Notably, all data are routine clinically-acquired, multi-site multiparametric magnetic resonance imaging (mpMRI) scans of brain tumor patients. The BraTS 2024 challenge participants are able to obtain the training and validation data of the challenge at any point from the Synapse platform. These data will be used to develop, containerize, and evaluate their algorithms in unseen validation data until August 2024, when the organizers will stop accepting new submissions and evaluate the submitted algorithms in the hidden testing data.
